rado. Red Mc\nClures. U. 8. No. 1. 1.47*4-55: North Da\nkota, Bliss Triumphs. 90 per cent U. 8. No.\n1. 1.15.\nBOSTON WOOL MARKET.\nBOSTON, Dec. 10 <U. 8. Dspgrt\nment of Agriculture).\u2014The tone in the\nBoston wool market today continued to\nshow improvement.\nIncreased firmness wfas being shown in\nmost grades of domestic greasy combing\nwqqIs. In addition to some further busi\nness in fine Western grown wools, lower\ngrades were getting inquiries from mills.\nA little quarter blooa fleece wool was\n.sold at prices mostly on the low side ol\nFan*c* 53 to 57 cents scoured basis,\nwhich iw comparable to 30 to 32 cents\nin the grease for Ohio wools. Bids just\nunder this range have been made upon\nsiEable quantities and were refused.\nNEW YORK SUGAR.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 10 UP.\u2014Declines of\na point or more in the No. 3 sugar fu\ntures contract today were recovered In later\ntrading, while the No. 4 showed little\nchange.\nMarch No. 3 sold up from 2.30 to 2.31\nand July from 2.31 to 2.33, with the mar\nket at the beginning of the last hour hold\ning around the best, or 1 point net higher.\nNo. 4 contract, where March sold at\n1.14*4 and July at 1.18. was net un\nchanged.\nMETAL MARKET.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 10 UP.\u2014Copper,\nsteady; electrolytic spot and future. 10.25\n11; export. 10.15. Tin. steady; spot and\nfuture. 44.75 nominal. Lead, steady;\nspot. New York, 5.00-5.05; East St. Louis,\n4.85. Zinc steady; East St. Louis spot\nand future, 5-00. Iron, aluminum, anti\nmony. quicksilver, platinum and wol\nframite unchanged.\nCrown Drug Co.\u2014November sales\nwere up 1.7 per cent, two months up\n0.8 per cent.\nWeek\u2019s Gain of 11.6 Per\nCent Leaves Total of 16.4\nPer Cent Below 1936.\nNEW YORK. Dec. Jo.\u2014The Asso\nciated Press seasonally adjusted weekly\nIndex of freight carloadings. based on\n1820-30 as 100. advanced today to\n60.n compared with 08.8 the previous\nweek and 83.1 a year ago.\nRange of recent years\n1037. 1930. 1935. 1034. 1933.\nHigh _ 82.2 84 5 71.7 65.9 07 3\nLow 68.1 60.7 58.0 59.5 47.7\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe Association of American Rail\nroads reported today 623,337 cars of\nrevenue freight were loaded during\nthe week ending last Saturday.\nThis was an increase of 64,710 cars,\nor 11.6 per cent, compared with the\npreceding week; a decrease of 121,958,\nor 16.4 per cent, compared with a year\nago, and a decrease of 163,735, or 20.8\nper cent, compared with 1930.\nThe report classified the loadings as\nfollows:\nThis Last Year\nWeek. Week. Ago.\nMiscellaneous 244 430* 28 03(1* 56 \"63\nLess than carlot 155.065* 20.443* 13 762\nCoal 126.168* 5.163* 41.910\nGram and\nproducts _ 37.783* 4.866* 1,495\nWestern dis\ntricts _ 23 401* 2.902* 2.381\nLive stock_ 15.174* 2.812* 2 673\nWestern\ndistricts 11,449* 1,874* 2 088\nForest products 28.021* 2.004 5 71\"\nOre _ 10 518* 1.160* 2 353\nCoke _ 6.169* 668t 5.477\nIncrease,\nt Decrease.\nRevenue freight carloadings on railroads\nreporting today for the week ended De\ncember 4 included\nDec. 4. Prev wk. Yr. ago.\nChes A- Ohio _ 26.128 25.375 35.561\nChi A' N W _ 23.665 21.715 28.055\n111 Central __ 32.426 28.978 36.094\nMo Pac _ 23.840 21.435 26.610\nN Y Central __ 70.481 63.048 89.306\nNorfolk A- W_ 20.741 10.327 20 1\"8\nPennsylvania 84.798 77.788 111.954\nSt L-San Fran 13.560 12.093 15.386\nSouthern Pac 36.314 32,343 38.523\nVIRGINIA FACTORY\nOUTPUT CLIMBS\nValue of 1936 Production Jumps\n15 Per Cent Above 1935 and\n16 Per Cent Over 1929.\nBy the Associated Press.\nRICHMOND, Va.. Dec. 10.\u2014The\nvalue of Virginia's manufactured prod\nucts totaled *902,348.968 in 1936, an\nincrease of 15 per cent over the 1935\nfigure and 16 per cent over the *779.\n691.363 figure for the boom year 1929.\nJohn Hapkins Hall. jr.. head of the\nState Department of Labor and Indus\ntry, revealed In his annual report to\nGov. Peery.\nIn terms of the higher prices of\n1929. he added, the 1936 value repre\nsented a 36 per cent increase over the\n1929 value.\nThe number of wage earners and\nthe amount of wages paid also in\ncreased. but not in proportion to the\nadvance in the value of manufactured\nproducts, it was reported. The aver\nage number of workers in manufac\nturing in 1936 was 160,793, an increase\nof 6.6 per cent over the 1935 average\nand 12.9 over the 1929 level. Total\nwages paid advanced 14 per cent over\nthe 1935 total and 10 per cent over the\n1929 total in terms of 1929 prices.\n\"This is in contrast, to the 36 per\ncent advanced by value of product in\nterms of 1929 prices,\u201d Hall said. \"The\nabove figures indicate that purchas\ning power is not keeping pace with in\ndustrial production. If there is to be\nany permanent prosperity in a society\ncharacterized by mass production, the\npurchasing power of the masses must\nbe maintained.\u201d\nCOTTON CROP JUMPS\nIN NORTH CAROLINA\nBy the Associated Press.\nRALEIGH, N. C\u201e Dec. 10\u2014Of\nficials of the State Department of\nAgriculture said North Carolina\nfarmers had harvested 369.936,000\npounds of cotton this year, an in\ncrease of 29 per cent over the 285,\n186.000-pound crop of last year.\nTar Heel cotton farmers cultivated\n15 per cent more acres than in 1936,\nW. H. Rhodes, department statistician,\nreported, and harvested 336 pounds\nto an acre, compared with 298 pounds\nlast year.\nHolders Accept\nTreasury Offer to\nExchange Issues\nBy the Associated Press.\nSecretary Morgenthau said today\nholders of virtually all of the $277,\n000.000 worth of Treasury notes ma\nturing February 1 have accepted an\noffer to exchange their securities for\nnew issues instead of receiving cash.\nThey were offered either eight-year\n25 2 per cent bonds or five-year 1%\nper cent Treasury notes. Since $450,\n000,000 worth of the new securities\nalso were offered for cash sale, the\nexchanges will bring the total financ\ning to approxtpiately $725,000,000.\nThe Secretary also said cash bids\nfor the $250,000,000 worth of new\nbonds totaled $4,084,000,000. Because\nof this near-record subscription the\nTreasury will sell each bidder only\none $1,000 bond plus 7 per cent of the\nbonds asked above $1,000.\nCash bids for the $200,000,000 worth\nof new notes aggregated $2,702,000,000.\nEach bidder will be allotted $1,000\nplus 8 per cent of the amount asked\nabove $1,000.\n\nWEEK\u2019S NEW FINANCING\nAT $35,151,385 LEVEL\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 10. (A>).\u2014New\nfinancing for the week ended Decem\nber 9 amounted to $35,151,385, with\nmunicipal issues comprising the bulk\nof the total, a special compilation by\nPoor s Publishing Co. showed today.'\nThe comparative table showed:\nWeek ended\nDee. 10. Year aeo.\nMunicipal_..$20,832,721 $7.467.ntlO\nIndustrial _ 10,000.000 1.500.000\nPublic utilities 30,250.000\nRailroads __ 10,000.000\nStocks 3.933.664 1,558,969\nMiscellaneous _ 385.000 42.899,500\nTotal $35,151,385 $93,675,469\nm\nBURLY TOBACCO PRICE\nIMPROVES IN VIRGINIA\nBy the Associated Press.\nRICHMOND, Va., Dec. 10\u2014Burley\ntobacco brought prices ranging up\nto $50 per hundredweight yesterday\nat Abingdon. Virginia's only burley\nmarket, and averaged $22.77 for\n470.104 pounds.\nBoth volume and average price bet\ntered the season s opening sales Wed\nnesday.\nDark-fired, sun-cured and bright\nleaf also found ready buyers on the\nVirginia auction centers. The Lynch\nburg dark-fired market sold 599 981\npounds during the four-day period\nended yesterday at an average of $9.59,\nand reported a season sale to date of\n1,093.359 pounds.\nYesterday's sales and average prices\nfor other Virginia markets included:\nBlackstone 'dark' 66.784 510 54\nDrakes Branch (dark) 27.h:\u00bbh 12 in\nRichmond (Sun-cured)_25.000 x .no\n\u2022South Boston (blight).. 286.000 lti.lib\n\u2022Wednesday sales.\nDISTRIBUTION ORDERED.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 10 (Special).\u2014\nDirectors of Capital Administration\nCo., Ltd., have declared the regular\nquarterly dividend of 75 cents a share\non the $3 cumulative preferred stock,\nseries A, payable January 1. to stock\nholders of record December 20.\nTO\nGeneral Business Outlook\nMust Improve, Says Stand\nard Statistics.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tho Star.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 10.\u2014A realistic\nview of the building situation indi\ncates that even if the full program\nadvocated by the President becomes\neffective, an important rise in the\nvolume of residential construction\nmust hinge first on restoration of\nconfidence in the general business\noutlook and, second, on the creation\nof large scale residential building\norganizations using mass production\nmethods, in the opinion of the Stand\nard Statistics Co.\nAnother upturn in construction\nactivity may be generated some time\nnext year, but its initial stages will\nbe slow. The prospect for recovery\nIn building is not a factor to be con\nsidered of immediate significance in\nthe outlook for business.\nThe President\u2019s special message on\nhousing is encouraging not only be\ncause of the specific recommenda\ntions for further liberalization of\nfinancing on residential construction,\nbut also because it officially recog\nnized the restrictive effects of the\nsharp advances in labor costs and\nmaterials last spring.\nBuilding activity is primarily a func\ntion of private industry, and the vol\nume of construction depends strictly\non the state of business confidence.\nWhile Government aid or direct sub\nsidies may provide direct stimulants,\nthey are definitely a secondary factor\nin the longer term building outlook.\nThe fact that the President has pro\nposed merely a liberalization of\nfinance terms through lower interest\ncharges and higher mortgage guar\nantees, rather than that the Govern\nment enter bluilding directly, Is gen\nerally approved, therefore, within the\nindustry itself.\nHow far the attack on building\ncosts may go, of course, is problemati\ncal. It has long since been demon\nstrated that rising costa are less of\na deterrent to building than loss of\nconfidence in the general business out\nlook. However, the type of building\nwhich it is desired to stimulate is\nthe housing for low-income groups,\nIn the last analysis costs of this type\nof housing must be radically reduced\nthrough changed design and large\nscale operation If a building boom is\nto be created.\nODD-LOT PURCHASES\nLARGER THAN SALES\nbi the Associated Press.\nCustomers\u2019 orders to buy exceeded\nselling orders in odd-lot transaction!\non the New York Stock Exchange In\n1 the week ended December 4.\nThe Securities and Exchange Com.\nj mission reported that buying order.i\ntotaled *35.359,886, or $4,863,081 in\nexcess of the value of selling orders.\nOdd-lot orders to buy totaled 42.871\nfor 1.068,076 shares. 8elmg order!\ntotaled 32,515 for 880,510 shares.\nNOTICE OF REDEMPTION.\nTHE POTOMAC JOINT STOCK LAND\nBANK OF ALEXANDRIA. VIRGINIA.\nS PER CENT BONDS.\n(COUPON AND REGISTERED)\nDated January 1. 1978\nCallable January 1. 1938\nDue January 1. 1858\nNotice is hereby given. as provided by ru!r\u00bb\nand regulations prescribed by the Farn\nCredit Administration, that the under,\nsigned. The Potomac Joint Stock Land\nBank at Alexandria. Virginia, has called\ni for redemption on January 1. 1938 all ol\nits outstanding bonds above described.\nSaid bonds are payable at par upon pres\nentation at The Riggs National Bank\nWashington. D. C.. on and after January L\n1938. on which date interest thereon will\ni cease.\nDated: December 1. 1937.\nTHE POTOMAC JOINT STOCK LANE\nBANK of Alexandria, Virginia\nBy (Signed) DONALD S. NACE\nAttest: President.\n(Signed) AUDREY B CARROLL\nAsst. fVsc.rPtsrv\nFirst\nTrust\nLoans\nFor Purchasing a Home or\nRE-FINANCING\nEXPIRING TRUSTS\nNO COMMISSION CHARGE\nNO RENEWALS REQUIRED\nauiLoma 4 iota\n-bocmtion Council fee\nRATIONAL\nON OCR. SUDtRvtSiON\nU. TRtASURV\n<INTH STRtl\nfa777//777//7/77/?777777777777777777777777777Z\nX\nFirst Mortgage 5\nI LOANS I\n\n5 IMPROVED REAL ESTATE\nAt 5%\n\nMonthly Paymentt X\nIf Preferred X\nX\nConstruction Loans\nDistrict of Columbia,\nNearby Md. end Virginia\njwM. J. FLATHER, Jr.j\nInc.\n1508 H St. it NA. 175S 5\nymatmmmfjrmnMmujammmk\nH\nFirst\nMortgage\nMoney\nFob\nCONSTRUCTION\nLOANS\nLOANS ON\nIMPROVED\nPROPERTY\nin the\nDistrict of Columbia\nNearby Maryland\nand Virginia\nAlso\nMonthly Payment\nLoans\nI\nPrompt Action\nB. F. SAUL CO.\n925 15th Street Natl. 2100\n_","height":"31132","width":"22396"}}
